---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import FlowDiagram from "@/components/FlowDiagram.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;

const snapshot = [
  { label: "Role", value: "Product Manager (0 → 1 lead)" },
  { label: "Domain", value: "Semiconductor manufacturing" },
  { label: "Type", value: "Enterprise agent platform · internal product" },
  {
    label: "Confidentiality",
    value: "Methodology abstracted · internals private",
  },
];

// Grounded in the public architecture write-up on the AI Stack page: dual-mode
// design, a layered tools/skills/agents asset model, governance by design, and
// automation orchestration. Kept deliberately generic — no internal system names.
const architectureSteps = [
  { label: "Manual Expert Workflow", note: "the starting point" },
  { label: "Agent Platform", note: "dual-mode: chat + build", emphasis: true },
  { label: "Tools · Skills · Agents", note: "layered asset model" },
  { label: "Grounded Configuration", note: "domain knowledge in, not guessed" },
  {
    label: "Governance Layer",
    note: "sandbox + human-in-the-loop",
    emphasis: true,
  },
  { label: "Automation Orchestration", note: "repeatable, auditable runs" },
];
---

<Layout
  title={`Enterprise Agent Platform: 0 → 1 — ${config.site.title}`}
  description="Case study: leading an enterprise agent platform from an ambiguous start to a working product in semiconductor manufacturing — constraints, product decisions, and how harness, loop, and vibe-coding methods shaped it."
  ogImage="/og/enterprise-agent-platform.png"
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main pageTitle="Enterprise Agent Platform: 0 → 1" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-sm">
      <a
        href={getRelativeLocaleUrl("zh", "projects/enterprise-agent-platform")}
        class="text-accent hover:underline"
      >
        阅读中文版
      </a>
    </p>

    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      How I took an enterprise agent platform from an ambiguous starting point
      to a working product inside a semiconductor manufacturing organization.
      This page abstracts the product methodology — the decisions, the
      reasoning, and the working system behind them — while keeping internal
      data, system names, and metrics private.
    </p>

    <div class="border-border mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Agent Platform
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Enterprise AI
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        0 → 1
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Governance by Design
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Industrial
      </span>
    </div>

    <div
      class="border-border bg-border mt-6 grid gap-px overflow-hidden rounded-lg border sm:grid-cols-2"
    >
      {
        snapshot.map(item => (
          <div class="bg-background p-4">
            <p class="text-muted-foreground text-xs font-medium tracking-wide uppercase">
              {item.label}
            </p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm">{item.value}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>

    <div
      class="border-border bg-muted/30 text-muted-foreground mt-6 rounded-lg border p-4 text-sm"
    >
      <strong class="text-foreground">A note on confidentiality.</strong> This is
      real product work in an enterprise setting. Everything here is written at the
      level of methodology and product reasoning. No proprietary data, internal system
      names, customer information, or confidential metrics are published. Where a
      real number would make a claim concrete, I mark it as a placeholder rather than
      invent one.
    </div>

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  1. CONTEXT  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">
      Context: an ambiguous starting point
    </h2>
    <p>
      The organization had deep domain expertise and a large body of
      institutional knowledge, but that knowledge lived in people, spreadsheets,
      and legacy tools. Skilled engineers spent a meaningful share of their time
      on repetitive, judgment-light work: looking things up, reconciling data
      across systems, and manually running procedures that followed known rules.
      There was clear appetite for AI, but no shared definition of what an
      "agent platform" should be, who it was for, or how success would be
      measured.
    </p>
    <!-- TODO(Bryan): Add 1–2 concrete, shareable specifics about the starting
         state if you're comfortable — e.g. the class of tasks targeted first,
         or roughly how many people/teams were in the initial audience. -->
    <p>
      <em class="text-muted-foreground"
        >[PLACEHOLDER: e.g., "The first target workflow was X — a process that
        took a domain expert Y hours per week and touched Z different internal
        systems."]</em
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      What the business <strong>had</strong>: domain experts, proprietary
      process knowledge, existing data (however messy), and executive interest.
      What it <strong>lacked</strong>: a product shape for that interest, a
      reliable way to put AI in front of sensitive workflows, and a path from
      "impressive demo" to "something people trust enough to use daily."
    </p>

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  2. CONSTRAINTS  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">
      Constraints: what "enterprise" and "industrial" really impose
    </h2>
    <p>
      The hard part of this product was never the model. It was building
      something that could survive the constraints of an industrial enterprise.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Data sensitivity.</strong> Process and operational data is commercially
        sensitive and access-controlled. The platform had to assume that data cannot
        leave certain boundaries, and that "just send it to the model" is often not
        an option. Grounding had to happen without leaking.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Domain experts as the real users.</strong> The people who would judge
        this product know their domain far better than any model does. They are quick
        to lose trust in a system that is confidently wrong. The bar was not "sounds
        plausible" — it was "an expert would sign off on this."
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Legacy workflows and systems.</strong> Real work already flowed through
        established tools and procedures. A platform that ignored them and demanded
        new behavior would be rejected regardless of how good the AI was. It had to
        meet existing workflows where they were.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>A high reliability bar.</strong> In a manufacturing context, a wrong
        action is not a cosmetic bug. The cost of a confidently wrong automated step
        is high, so the safe default had to be "propose and wait for a human," not
        "act."
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  3. KEY DECISIONS  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Key product decisions</h2>
    <p>
      A handful of decisions did most of the work. Each was a product call I
      made and can defend — not a technical detail delegated to implementation.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium">
      1. A dual-mode platform, not a chatbot
    </h3>
    <p>
      The platform separates a conversational mode (ask, explore, get answers)
      from a build mode (compose and configure reusable automation). Framing it
      this way avoided the trap of shipping "another chat box" and instead made
      the product a place where capability accumulates. The reasoning: a chatbot
      is consumed; a platform is built on. Only the second one compounds in
      value over time.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium">
      2. A layered tools / skills / agents asset model
    </h3>
    <p>
      Rather than a monolith, capability is layered: low-level <strong
        >tools</strong
      > (typed actions the system can take), composable <strong>skills</strong>
      (reusable procedures built from tools), and <strong>agents</strong> (which apply
      skills to a goal). This gave non-engineers a mental model they could reason
      about, made capabilities auditable, and let the platform grow by accretion instead
      of rewrites.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium">
      3. Governance as a design principle, not a feature bolted on later
    </h3>
    <p>
      Sandbox isolation and human-in-the-loop approval were designed in from the
      start, not retrofitted. The default posture is that an agent
      <em>proposes</em> an action and a human <em>approves</em> it before anything
      with real-world consequence happens. In an industrial setting this is what makes
      adoption possible at all: experts will try a system that cannot act behind their
      back long before they'll try one that can.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium">
      4. Grounded configuration over prompt cleverness
    </h3>
    <p>
      Reliability came from grounding the system in real domain configuration
      and data — structured context the platform reads — rather than from
      ever-longer prompts. This connects directly to the ontology work elsewhere
      on this site: the more the system's knowledge is structured and explicit,
      the less it has to guess.
      <a
        href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "projects/prompt-to-ontology")}
        class="text-accent hover:underline">See Prompt-to-Ontology →</a
      >
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-medium">
      5. Start with one workflow, prove trust, then generalize
    </h3>
    <p>
      Instead of a broad horizontal launch, the platform earned its place on one
      concrete, painful workflow first. Winning trust on a single real task
      created the credibility (and the reusable assets) to expand — a sequencing
      decision, not an accident.
    </p>
    <!-- TODO(Bryan): If shareable, name the first workflow you anchored on and
         why it was the right wedge. This is the single most persuasive detail
         you could add to this section. -->

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  4. HOW I WORKED  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">
      How I worked: methodology in practice
    </h2>
    <p>
      The frameworks I write about in the playbook are not post-hoc theory —
      they are how this platform actually got built. Concretely:
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Vibe-coded prototypes as the engineering blueprint.</strong>
        Instead of handing engineering a static PRD, I used PM-led, coding-agent-assisted
        prototyping to produce working prototypes of key flows. A clickable, functional
        prototype removed ambiguity from the spec and became the reference implementation
        the team could build against.
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/vibe-coding")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline">Vibe Coding →</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Harness engineering to make agent output trustworthy.</strong>
        The reliability bar above is a harness problem: defining the context, tools,
        constraints, and acceptance criteria an agent operates within. Much of my
        work was designing that environment so the platform's own agents produced
        output an expert would accept.
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/harness-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline">Harness Engineering →</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Loop engineering to improve across iterations.</strong> Feedback from
        domain experts fed back into configuration, constraints, and acceptance criteria
        rather than living in someone's head. Each cycle left behind an artifact the
        next cycle could build on.
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/loop-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline">Loop Engineering →</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>

    <FlowDiagram
      steps={architectureSteps}
      caption="The shape of the platform, abstracted: a manual expert workflow becomes a dual-mode platform built on layered assets, grounded in real configuration, and gated by a governance layer before anything runs automatically."
    />

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  5. OUTCOMES  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Outcomes</h2>
    <p>
      The honest summary: the platform moved from "there is interest in AI" to a
      working product that real users engage with on real work. Because this is
      internal enterprise work, the specific numbers stay private — the
      placeholders below mark where I can share directional results in
      conversation.
    </p>
    <!-- TODO(Bryan): Replace each placeholder with a real (or safely rounded /
         directional) figure you're comfortable publishing. If a number is too
         sensitive to share even directionally, delete that bullet rather than
         weaken it. Do NOT publish anything under NDA. -->
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Adoption:</strong>
        <em class="text-muted-foreground"
          >[PLACEHOLDER: e.g., "went from 0 to N active users / M teams using it
          for real tasks within X months of the first internal release."]</em
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Cycle time:</strong>
        <em class="text-muted-foreground"
          >[PLACEHOLDER: e.g., "reduced the target workflow from ~X hours of
          expert time to ~Y minutes, with a human still approving the final
          step."]</em
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Qualitative signals:</strong>
        <em class="text-muted-foreground"
          >[PLACEHOLDER: e.g., "domain experts began requesting new skills
          themselves," or "a workflow the team originally resisted automating
          became the most-used one."]</em
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Reusable assets:</strong> a layered library of tools and skills, a
        governance pattern other teams could adopt, and a validated product shape
        for what an enterprise agent platform is — independent of any one workflow.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- ─────────────────────────  6. WHAT I'D DO DIFFERENTLY  ───────────────────────── -->
    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">What I'd do differently</h2>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>Invest in evaluation earlier.</strong> The instinct to build capability
        outruns the instinct to measure it. A lightweight, domain-grounded eval harness
        from day one would have made "is this good enough for an expert to trust?"
        a measured question instead of a judgment call.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Define the governance UX sooner.</strong> Governance was designed
        in early, but the <em>experience</em> of reviewing and approving agent actions
        is itself a product surface — and the faster that feels natural, the faster
        experts extend trust. I'd treat the approval flow as a first-class design
        problem from the start.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Resist horizontal pull for longer.</strong> Success on the first workflow
        creates pressure to generalize everywhere at once. I'd hold the line on depth-before-breadth
        more firmly — one workflow that experts genuinely rely on is worth more than
        five they tolerate.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <!-- TODO(Bryan): Add anything you learned that only you would know — a
         specific wrong turn, an assumption that didn't hold, a stakeholder
         dynamic. This section is most credible when at least one item is
         unmistakably from lived experience. -->

    <div
      class="border-border bg-muted/30 mt-8 flex flex-col gap-3 rounded-lg border p-5 sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between"
    >
      <div>
        <p class="font-medium">The methodology behind this, in the open</p>
        <p class="text-muted-foreground text-sm">
          The frameworks referenced above are written up in full in the
          playbook.
        </p>
      </div>
      <a
        href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
        class="bg-accent text-accent-foreground inline-flex shrink-0 items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
      >
        Read the Playbook &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "projects/prompt-to-ontology")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Prompt-to-Ontology
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/harness-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Harness Engineering
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/vibe-coding")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Vibe Coding
        </a>
        <a
          href="https://wenhaoyu-bryan.github.io/agent-anatomy/"
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          Agent Anatomy ↗
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
